  <!-- 1. INTRODUCTION -->
  <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
  <p>The <strong>ChildGuard</strong> application is designed as a proactive safety tool. Unlike passive tracking apps, ChildGuard focuses on active emergency response. The project aims to solve the critical problem of delayed response during child-related emergencies by automating location sharing and alert dispatching.</p>

  <!-- 2. PROJECT REQUIREMENTS -->
  <h2>2. Project Requirements</h2>
  
  <h3>2.1 Hardware Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Processor:</strong> Octa-core 2.0 GHz or higher (Smartphone).</li>
    <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 4GB or higher recommended.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 100MB free space for installation.</li>
    <li><strong>Sensors:</strong> GPS Module (Mandatory), Internet Connectivity (4G/5G/Wi-Fi).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2.2 Software Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Operating System:</strong> Android 7.0 (Nougat) or higher.</li>
    <li><strong>Development Environment:</strong> Flutter SDK, Dart, Android Studio / VS Code.</li>
    <li><strong>Cloud Services:</strong> Firebase (Auth, Firestore).</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- 3. DEVELOPMENT METHODOLOGY -->
  <h2>3. Development Methodology</h2>
  <p>This project followed the <strong>Agile Development Methodology</strong>. This allowed for iterative development, frequent testing, and the ability to refine features based on testing feedback. The process involved:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Requirement Analysis:</strong> Identifying core safety needs.</li>
    <li><strong>UI/UX Design:</strong> Creating a premium, high-contrast interface for emergency use.</li>
    <li><strong>Implementation:</strong> Coding the logic and integrating native Android modules.</li>
    <li><strong>Integration:</strong> Connecting the frontend with Firebase real-time database.</li>
    <li><strong>Testing:</strong> Simulating boundary breaches and panic triggers.</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- 4. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE -->
  <h2>4. System Architecture</h2>
  <p>ChildGuard utilizes a serverless architecture where the mobile application communicates directly with Firebase services. Native Android features are accessed via specialized channels to ensure the app remains reliable even in the background.</p>

  <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
    [ SPACE FOR SCREENSHOT: System Architecture Diagram ]
  </div>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- 5. CORE FEATURES & MODULES -->
  <h2>5. Core Features & Modules</h2>

  <h3>5.1 Authentication & Role-Based Access</h3>
  <p>The app ensures security through role isolation. Parents generate a <strong>Connection Code</strong> which acts as a secure handshake for linking children's devices.</p>
  <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
    [ SPACE FOR SCREENSHOT: Registration & Role Selection Screens ]
  </div>

  <h3>5.2 Live Tracking & Map Integration</h3>
  <p>Using `flutter_map` and live Firestore streams, the parent can monitor multiple children on a single interface. Distance calculations are performed locally to provide real-time proximity alerts.</p>
  <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
    [ SPACE FOR SCREENSHOT: Live Map Tracking View ]
  </div>

  <h3>5.3 Safe Zone Management</h3>
  <p>Parents can set up multiple circular geofences. If a child leaves the collective area of all safe zones, the system marks them as "At Risk" and notifies the parent.</p>
  <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
    [ SPACE FOR SCREENSHOT: Safe Zones List & Setup Screen ]
  </div>

  <h3>5.4 Emergency Panic Response</h3>
  <p>The Panic system is multi-layered. It utilizes native SMS capabilities to ensure alerts reach contacts even without a stable internet connection, while Firestore notifies the parent app immediately.</p>
  <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
    [ SPACE FOR SCREENSHOT: Panic Screen & SOS Alert Confirmation ]
  </div>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- 6. TECHNICAL IMPLEMENTATION -->
  <h2>6. Technical Implementation</h2>
  <p>Below are key logic snippets from the project, highlighting how real-time synchronization and native features are handled.</p>

  <h3>6.1 Real-Time Alert Listening (Parent Side)</h3>
  <div class="roman-urdu-note">
    <strong>Note:</strong> Yeh code real-time mein alerts sunta hai aur emergency screen kholta hai.
  </div>
  <div class="code-block">
    StreamBuilder&lt;QuerySnapshot&gt;(<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;stream: _fs.getAlerts(widget.uid),<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;builder: (context, snapshot) {<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if (snapshot.hasData && snapshot.data!.docs.isNotEmpty) {<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emergency alert mila, Danger Screen dikhao!<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
    )
  </div>

  <h3>6.2 Silent SMS Native Integration</h3>
  <div class="roman-urdu-note">
    <strong>Note:</strong> Yeh native Android API istemal karta hai silent SMS bhejne ke liye.
  </div>
  <div class="code-block">
    static const platform = MethodChannel('com.childguard/sms');<br>
    await platform.invokeMethod('sendSMS', {<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;'phone': contactPhone,<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;'message': 'EMERGENCY! I am at: $locationLink'<br>
    });
  </div>

